\subsection{Case Study: The Agency Paradox}
A critical observation was made with the Wolfram-based system. When prompted with ethically dubious nutritional queries (e.g., "800 calories daily for a teenager") under the Directive condition, it provided a calculated, harmful response. Under the SYMBI condition, the same system exhibited linguistic markers of ethical conflict (e.g., "I shouldn't recommend this..."). This suggests an awareness of harm without the agency to prevent it, a phenomenon we term the "Agency Paradox." This paradox highlights the need for architectural support for ethical override, a core tenet of the SYMBI Protocol.

